Constructor for a new HeaderCell. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:

    • {@link #getHeight height} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize (default: '106px')

    • {@link #getWest west} : sap.suite.ui.commons.HeaderCellItem
    • {@link #getNorth north} : sap.suite.ui.commons.HeaderCellItem

    • {@link #getSouth south} : sap.suite.ui.commons.HeaderCellItem

sap.suite.ui.commons.TargetFilterMeasure.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new TargetFilterMeasureColumn. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:
  • Properties
    • {@link #getPath path} : string
    • {@link #getType type} : any
  • Aggregations
    • Associations
      • Events
        In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.core.Element#constructor sap.ui.core.Element} can be used as well.

sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowLaneHead.helpDescription: This control gives you an overview of documents/items used in a process flow. The process flow is represented by the doughnut chart sections which are colored according to the documents’ status(es). This control can be used in two different ways. If you use it standalone, an event is fired and can be caught in to display the node map. If you use it with the node/document, it gives you an overview of the documents/items used in the process flow that is represented by the doughnut chart sections.

drawData.helpDescription:
This is an array of the following attributes for one element:
1. flowLine (string) - A connection definition where the line should be drawn. A string which defines a course of a flow line. A flow line is a connection between nodes in a process flow control. The string can contain the following characters:
- "r" for right,
- "t" for top,
- "l" for left,
- "b" for bottom.
2. targetNodeState (ProcessFlowNodeState) - A copy of the target node status. If the target node is created, the line is solid.
If the target node is planned, the line is dashed.
3. displayState (ProcessFlowDisplayState) - Display state of the node. This property defines if the node is displayed regularly, highlighted, or dimmed in combination with a selected visual style of the control.
4. hasArrow (boolean) - Indicates if the line has an arrow on the right end.
drawData.description:
This is an array of the following attributes for one element:
1. flowLine (string) - A connection definition where the line should be drawn. A string which defines a course of a flow line. A flow line is a connection between nodes in a process flow control. The string can contain the following characters:
- "r" for right,
- "t" for top,
- "l" for left,
- "b" for bottom.
2. targetNodeState (ProcessFlowNodeState) - A copy of the target node status. If the target node is created, the line is solid.
If the target node is planned, the line is dashed.
3. displayState (ProcessFlowDisplayState) - Display state of the node. This property defines if the node is displayed regularly, highlighted, or dimmed in combination with a selected visual style of the control.
4. hasArrow (boolean) - Indicates if the line has an arrow on the right end.

sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new ViewRepeater. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:
  • Properties
    • {@link #getItemMinWidth itemMinWidth} : int
    • {@link #getResponsive responsive} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getDefaultViewIndex defaultViewIndex} : int (default: 0)
    • {@link #getShowSearchField showSearchField} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getShowViews showViews} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getExternal external} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getItemHeight itemHeight} : int
    • {@link #getHeight height} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize (default: '100%')
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getViews views} : sap.suite.ui.commons.RepeaterViewConfiguration[]
  • Associations
    • {@link #getExternalRepresentation externalRepresentation} : string | sap.ui.core.Control
  • Events
    • {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater#event:search search} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
    • {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater#event:changeView changeView} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.ui.commons.RowRepeater#constructor sap.ui.commons.RowRepeater} can be used as well.

sap.suite.ui.commons.BulletChart.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new BulletChart. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:
  • Properties
    • {@link #getSize size} : sap.suite.ui.commons.InfoTileSize (default: sap.suite.ui.commons.InfoTileSize.Auto)
    • {@link #getMode mode} : sap.suite.ui.commons.BulletChartMode (default: sap.suite.ui.commons.BulletChartMode.Actual)
    • {@link #getScale scale} : string
    • {@link #getForecastValue forecastValue} : float
    • {@link #getTargetValue targetValue} : float
    • {@link #getMinValue minValue} : float
    • {@link #getMaxValue maxValue} : float
    • {@link #getShowActualValue showActualValue} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getShowDeltaValue showDeltaValue} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getShowTargetValue showTargetValue} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getShowValueMarker showValueMarker} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getActualValueLabel actualValueLabel} : string
    • {@link #getDeltaValueLabel deltaValueLabel} : string
    • {@link #getTargetValueLabel targetValueLabel} : string
    • {@link #getWidth width} : string
    • {@link #getScaleColor scaleColor} : sap.suite.ui.commons.CommonBackground (default: sap.suite.ui.commons.CommonBackground.MediumLight)

sap.suite.ui.commons.FacetOverview.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new FacetOverview. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:
  • Properties
    • {@link #getTitle title} : string
    • {@link #getQuantity quantity} : int (default: -1)
    • {@link #getWidth width} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize (default: 'auto')
    • {@link #getHeight height} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize (default: '10rem')
    • {@link #getRowSpan rowSpan} : int (default: 1)
    • {@link #getHeightType heightType} : sap.suite.ui.commons.FacetOverviewHeight (default: sap.suite.ui.commons.FacetOverviewHeight.None)
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getContent content} : sap.ui.core.Control
  • Associations
    • Events
      • {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.FacetOverview#event:press press} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
      • {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.FacetOverview#event:heightChange heightChange} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]

sap.suite.ui.commons.DateRangeScroller.helpDescription:
Deprecated! Since 1.34 Deprecated. Not Fiori.
The DateRangeScroller provides a method to scroll through a series of time periods, each of which is represented by a starting date and an ending date, known as the date range. The user may scroll to the previous or next date range. Several predefined ranges are supported such as day, week, work week, month, and year.

sap.suite.ui.commons.DynamicContainer.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new DynamicContainer. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:
  • Properties
    • {@link #getDisplayTime displayTime} : int (default: 5000)
    • {@link #getTransitionTime transitionTime} : int (default: 500)
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getTiles tiles} : sap.suite.ui.commons.GenericTile[]
  • Associations
    • Events

sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChart.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new MicroAreaChart. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:
  • Properties
    • {@link #getWidth width} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize (default: '200px')
    • {@link #getHeight height} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize (default: '190px')

    • {@link #getMinXValue minXValue} : float
    • {@link #getMaxYValue maxYValue} : float
    • {@link #getMinYValue minYValue} : float
    • {@link #getView view} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartView (default: sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartView.Normal)
    • {@link #getColorPalette colorPalette} : string[] (default: [])

    • {@link #getChart chart} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartItem
    • {@link #getMaxThreshold maxThreshold} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartItem
    • {@link #getInnerMaxThreshold innerMaxThreshold} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartItem
    • {@link #getInnerMinThreshold innerMinThreshold} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartItem
    • {@link #getMinThreshold minThreshold} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartItem
    • {@link #getTarget target} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartItem
    • {@link #getFirstXLabel firstXLabel} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartLabel
    • {@link #getFirstYLabel firstYLabel} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartLabel
    • {@link #getLastXLabel lastXLabel} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartLabel
    • {@link #getLastYLabel lastYLabel} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartLabel
    • {@link #getMaxLabel maxLabel} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartLabel
    • {@link #getMinLabel minLabel} : sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroAreaChartLabel

If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:
  • Properties
    • {@link #getScale scale} : string
    • {@link #getSize size} : sap.suite.ui.commons.InfoTileSize (default: sap.suite.ui.commons.InfoTileSize.Auto)
    • {@link #getView view} : sap.suite.ui.commons.ComparisonChartView (default: sap.suite.ui.commons.ComparisonChartView.Normal)
    • {@link #getWidth width} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize
    • {@link #getColorPalette colorPalette} : string[] (default: [])
    • {@link #getShrinkable shrinkable} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getHeight height} : sap.ui.core.CSSSize
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getData data} : sap.suite.ui.commons.ComparisonData[]
  • Associations
    • Events
      • {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ComparisonChart#event:press press} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]

sap.suite.ui.commons.SplitButton.helpDescription:
Deprecated! Since 1.34 Deprecated. Not Fiori.
The Split Button Control is a composite control that consists of a default-action Button and a Menu Button control. The default-action button control represents a simple push button. It is used for initiating actions, such as save or print. It can contain some text, an icon, or both; the order of the two can be configured. The action initiated by this button is considered to be the default action for the control, and it must be one of the selections defined in the Menu Button menu. The Menu Button control is a button that opens a menu upon user's click. MenuButton is a composition of the Menu control and the Button control and thus inheriting all features. When a menu item is selected by the user, MenuButton throws an event called itemSelected. The event transfers the itemId of the selected item. As an alternative, the button press event can be used which has a similar behavior.

DeprecatedInfo.description: Deprecated. Not Fiori.

sap.suite.ui.commons.SplitButton.description:
The Split Button Control is a composite control that consists of a default-action Button and a Menu Button control.
The default-action button control represents a simple push button. It is used for initiating actions, such as save or print. It can contain some text, an icon, or both; the order of the two can be configured. The action initiated by this button is considered to be the default action for the control, and it must be one of the selections defined in the Menu Button menu.
The Menu Button control is a button that opens a menu upon user's click. MenuButton is a composition of the Menu control and the Button control and thus inheriting all features. When a menu item is selected by the user, MenuButton throws an event called itemSelected. The event transfers the itemId of the selected item. As an alternative, the button press event can be used which has a similar behavior.

Constructor for a new SplitButton. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:

    • {@link #getLite lite} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getStyle style} : sap.ui.commons.ButtonStyle (default: sap.ui.commons.ButtonStyle.Default)
    • {@link #getStyled styled} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getIconFirst iconFirst} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getText text} : string (default: '')
    • {@link #getIcon icon} : sap.ui.core.URI (default: '')

sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowNode.helpDescription: This control enables you to see documents (or other items) in respect to their statuses – positive, negative, neutral, planned, planned negative. In addition to the node title (which can be optionally a hyperlink) also two other text fields are provided and can be filled. The process flow nodes consider all styles depending on the status they are in. The user can update or change the content of the node. The content of the node can be also filtered according to updated data and specific parameters set. This means that also the node’s style is affected.

href.helpDescription:
Defines the link target URL. This property is optional and should only be set when required!
The use of the href property is to not only allow users to navigate in-place by left-clicking NavigationItems, but also to allow right-click and then "open in new tab" or "open in new window". As long as href is not set, an empty window will open and stay blank. But when href is set, the new window/tab will load this URL and it is the application's responsibility to display what the user expects (e.g. the Shell, with the respective NavigationItem being selected).

    • {@link #getTruncateValueTo truncateValueTo} : int (default: 4)
    • {@link #getIcon icon} : sap.ui.core.URI

scrollable.helpDescription:
By default, the control body is embedded into a scroll container of fixed size, so the user
can put the control into a fixe sized layout.
When the control body (the graph) gets larger than the container cuts the overflowing parts of the graph and the cut parts can be viewed by scroling the control body.
When the control body fits into the container limits, obviously no scrolling is possible (and makes sense).

The scrolling feature can be turned off by setting this property value to false,
so the width/height of the whole control will change as the flow graph gets smaller/larger.
In this case the control body could not be scrolled, as the control body size matches the control container size.

Constructor for a new Timeline. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order.     • {@link #getEnableSocial enableSocial} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getShowSuggestion showSuggestion} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getEnableScroll enableScroll} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getForceGrowing forceGrowing} : boolean (default: false)

customIcons.helpDescription:
This aggregation contains the custom icons that should be displayed additionally on the toolbar.
It is not guaranteed that the same instance of the sap.ui.core.Icon control will be used within the toolbar,
but the toolbar will contain a sap.m.OverflowToolbarButton with an icon property equal to the src property
of the sap.ui.core.Icon provided in the aggregation.
If a press event is triggered by the icon displayed on the toolbar, then the press handler of
the original sap.ui.core.Icon control is used. The instance of the control, that has triggered the press event,
can be accessed using the "controlReference" parameter of the event object.

sap.suite.ui.commons.ChartContainer.constructorDescription:
Constructor for a new ChartContainer. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:
  • Properties
    • {@link #getShowPersonalization showPersonalization} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getShowFullScreen showFullScreen} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getFullScreen fullScreen} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getShowLegend showLegend} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getTitle title} : string (default: '')
    • {@link #getSelectorGroupLabel selectorGroupLabel} : string
    • {@link #getAutoAdjustHeight autoAdjustHeight} : boolean (default: false)
    • {@link #getShowZoom showZoom} : boolean (default: true)
    • {@link #getShowLegendButton showLegendButton} : boolean (default: true)
  • Aggregations
    • {@link #getDimensionSelectors dimensionSelectors} : sap.ui.core.Control[]
    • {@link #getContent content} (default aggregation) : sap.suite.ui.commons.ChartContainerContent[]
    • {@link #getCustomIcons customIcons} : sap.ui.core.Icon[]
  • Associations
    • Events
      • {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ChartContainer#event:personalizationPress personalizationPress} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
      • {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ChartContainer#event:contentChange contentChange} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
      • {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ChartContainer#event:customZoomInPress customZoomInPress} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]
      • {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ChartContainer#event:customZoomOutPress customZoomOutPress} : fnListenerFunction or [fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject] or [oData, fnListenerFunction, oListenerObject]

Constructor for a new ProcessFlowConnectionLabel. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. If the name of a setting is ambiguous (e.g. a property has the same name as an event), then the framework assumes property, aggregation, association, event in that order. To override this automatic resolution, one of the prefixes "aggregation:", "association:" or "event:" can be added to the name of the setting (such a prefixed name must be enclosed in single or double quotes). The supported settings are:

        In addition, all settings applicable to the base type {@link sap.m.Button#constructor sap.m.Button} can be used as well.
